1) What OOP actually is
Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a way of organising code around objects.
A class is a blueprint, and an object is an instance created from that blueprint. Python’s official tutorial says classes bundle data and functionality together, and class instances can have attributes (data/state) and methods (behaviour). Python also supports core OOP features like inheritance and method overriding. [docs.python.org], [realpython.com], [geeksforgeeks.org]
Real-life analogy

Class = blueprint for a car
Object = your actual car
Attributes = colour, speed, brand
Methods = start(), stop(), brake()